  "prompt": "What are the good game stalls ideas that which gives much money than others at college fests?",
  "response": "When planning game stalls for a college fest, it's important to focus on ideas that are engaging, easy to set up, and have the potential to generate significant revenue. Here are some ideas that might be popular and profitable:\n\n1. **Ring Toss**: This classic game is easy to set up and play. Participants pay for a set number of rings to toss over bottles. Offering prizes for different levels of success can entice more players.\n\n2. **Balloon Dart Throw**: Players throw darts at balloons fixed on a wall. Each balloon could contain a paper for small to large prizes, making it exciting for players to try their luck multiple times.\n\n3. **Quiz and Trivia Games**: Organize themed quizzes, such as pop culture, current events, or niche topics. Charge an entry fee, and offer a prestigious prize to the winner. This can be attractive in college environments where students love to showcase their knowledge.\n\n4. **Basketball Challenge**: Set up a mini-basketball hoop and challenge players to make a certain number of baskets in a row. The simplicity and popularity of basketball often draw a crowd.\n\n5. **Escape Room**: A small, thematic escape room can be set up where groups pay to enter and solve puzzles within a given timeframe. This can be quite profitable if done well and marketed as a unique experience.\n\n6. **Treasure Hunt**: Organize a campus-wide treasure hunt with clues and tasks. Entry fees can be charged per team, and the nature of the game encourages group participation and excitement.\n\n7. **Photo Booth with Props**: Have a themed photo booth with fun props. Charge per photo session, and offer printed photos as keepsakes. This can be especially popular with social media-savvy college students.\n\n8. **Coffee Pong**: A twist on the classic beer pong, this version uses cups of coffee (or any non-alcoholic beverage). Players pay to participate, and small prizes can be offered for winners.\n\n9. **Spin the Wheel**: Set up a wheel with different sections representing prizes or challenges. Participants pay to spin, with the chance to win something every time. \n\n10. **Food Challenge**: Organize eating challenges like hot wing eating contests or \"finish this giant sandwich\" events. Charge entry fees and offer interesting prizes.\n\n11. **Virtual Reality (VR) Experience**: Offer a VR gaming experience where students pay for a set amount of playtime. The novelty and immersive nature of VR can draw a lot of interest.\n\nWhen setting up these stalls, consider factors such as initial setup costs, space availability, and the interest level of your target audience. It\u2019s also crucial to have well-organized staffing and clear rules for each game to ensure smooth operation.",
